#import "../book.typ": *

// ===================== BAR’CHU =====================
#startprayer("Bar’chu · The Call to Bless", "בָּרְכוּ", sec: "Sh’ma & Its Blessings")
#rubric([The leader calls; the community answers, then the leader repeats.])
#stanza("Barchú et Adonai ham’vorách.",
  "בָּרְכוּ אֶת יְיָ הַמְבֹרָךְ.")
#ritual([some bow here, rising at the Name])
#stanza("Barúch Adonai ham’vorách l’olám va’éd.",
  "בָּרוּךְ יְיָ הַמְבֹרָךְ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד.", label: "All")
#eng("Bless the Source of blessing.")
#engn("Blessed is the Source of blessing, now and forever.",
  [Bar’chu is the formal call to public prayer — the moment the gathering becomes a community. The Talmud teaches that these words require a minyan — a person praying alone cannot say them (Berakhot 21b); Bar’chu as the summons to prayer is discussed in Megillah 23b.])

// ===================== MA’ARIV ARAVIM =====================
#startprayer("Ma’ariv Aravim · Who Brings on Evening", "מַעֲרִיב עֲרָבִים", sec: "Sh’ma & Its Blessings")
#stanza("Barúch atá Adonai, Elohéinu mélech ha’olám, ashér bidvaró ma’arív aravím, b’chochmá potéach sh’arím, uvitvuná m’shané itím umachalíf et haz’maním, um’sadér et hakochavím b’mishm’rotéihem baraki’a kirtzonó.",
  "בָּרוּךְ אַתָּה יְיָ אֱלֹהֵינוּ מֶלֶךְ הָעוֹלָם אֲשֶׁר בִּדְבָרוֹ מַעֲרִיב עֲרָבִים בְּחָכְמָה פּוֹתֵחַ שְׁעָרִים וּבִתְבוּנָה מְשַׁנֶּה עִתִּים וּמַחֲלִיף אֶת־הַזְּמַנִּים וּמְסַדֵּר אֶת־הַכּוֹכָבִים בְּמִשְׁמְרוֹתֵיהֶם בָּרָקִיעַ כִּרְצוֹנוֹ.")
#stanza("Boré yom valáyla, golél or mipnéi chóshech v’chóshech mipnéi or, uma’avír yom umévi láyla, umavdíl bein yom uvéin láyla, Adonai tz’va’ót sh’mo.",
  "בּוֹרֵא יוֹם וָלָיְלָה גּוֹלֵל אוֹר מִפְּנֵי חֹשֶׁךְ וְחֹשֶׁךְ מִפְּנֵי אוֹר וּמַעֲבִיר יוֹם וּמֵבִיא לָיְלָה וּמַבְדִּיל בֵּין יוֹם וּבֵין לָיְלָה יְיָ צְבָאוֹת שְׁמוֹ.")
#chatimah("El chai v’kayám tamíd yimlóch aléinu l’olám va’éd. Barúch atá Adonai, hama’arív aravím.",
  "אֵל חַי וְקַיָּם תָּמִיד יִמְלֹךְ עָלֵינוּ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד. בָּרוּךְ אַתָּה יְיָ הַמַּעֲרִיב עֲרָבִים.")
#eng("Blessed are You, our God, Presence of the universe, whose word brings on the evening, whose wisdom opens the gates of the sky, whose understanding turns the seasons and sets the stars in their watches across the dome of heaven, just so.")
#eng("You create day and night, rolling light away before the dark and dark before the light. You make the day pass and bring on the night, drawing a line between day and night — Source of all being is Your name.")
#engn("Living and enduring God, may You guide us always, now and forever. Blessed are You, the One who brings on evening.",
  [The first blessing before the Sh’ma is a hymn to the daily miracle of nightfall. Its rabbinic authors chose to praise God not for a single act of creation long ago but for the ongoing turning of the sky — evening after evening — insisting that the natural order itself is a continuing gift.])

// ===================== AHAVAT OLAM =====================
#startprayer("Ahavat Olam · With Everlasting Love", "אַהֲבַת עוֹלָם", sec: "Sh’ma & Its Blessings")
#stanza("Ahavát olám beit Yisra’él amchá ahávta, Torá umitzvót, chukím umishpatím otánu limádta.",
  "אַהֲבַת עוֹלָם בֵּית יִשְׂרָאֵל עַמְּךָ אָהָבְתָּ תּוֹרָה וּמִצְוֹת חֻקִּים וּמִשְׁפָּטִים אוֹתָנוּ לִמַּדְתָּ.")
#stanza("Al ken Adonai Elohéinu b’shochvéinu uvkuméinu nasí’ach b’chukécha, v’nismách b’divréi Toratécha uvmitzvotécha l’olám va’éd.",
  "עַל כֵּן יְיָ אֱלֹהֵינוּ בְּשָׁכְבֵנוּ וּבְקוּמֵנוּ נָשִׂיחַ בְּחֻקֶּיךָ וְנִשְׂמַח בְּדִבְרֵי תוֹרָתֶךָ וּבְמִצְוֹתֶיךָ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד.")
#chatimah("Ki hem chayéinu v’órech yaméinu, uvahém neh’gé yomám valáyla. V’ahavatchá al tasír miménu l’olamím. Barúch atá Adonai, ohév amó Yisra’él.",
  "כִּי הֵם חַיֵּינוּ וְאֹרֶךְ יָמֵינוּ וּבָהֶם נֶהְגֶּה יוֹמָם וָלָיְלָה. וְאַהֲבָתְךָ אַל תָּסִיר מִמֶּנּוּ לְעוֹלָמִים. בָּרוּךְ אַתָּה יְיָ אוֹהֵב עַמּוֹ יִשְׂרָאֵל.")
#eng("With everlasting love You have loved the house of Israel, Your people: Torah and mitzvot, teachings and just ways — these You taught us.")
#eng("And so, our God, lying down and rising up, we will speak of Your teachings and delight in the words of Your Torah and its mitzvot, forever.")
#engn("For they are our life and the length of our days; on them we will meditate day and night. May Your love never depart from us. Blessed are You, the One who loves Your people Israel.",
  [The second blessing reframes revelation as intimacy: the gift of Torah is named as an act of love. Placed just before the Sh’ma, it teaches that the commandment to love God (which the Sh’ma will soon demand) is a response — we love because we have first been loved.])
